SIMPLE: stir
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stir
<hw>Stir</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Stirred</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Stirring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>stiren</ets>,
<ets>steren</ets>, <ets>sturen</ets>, AS. <ets>styrian</ets>; probably
akin to D. <ets>storen</ets> to disturb, G. <ets>st⟦oum⟧ren</ets>, OHG.
<ets>st⟦omac⟧ren</ets> to scatter, destroy. ⟦root⟧166.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To change the place of in any manner; to
move.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My foot I had never yet in five days been able to
<qex>stir</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To disturb the relative position of the particles
of, as of a liquid, by passing something through it; to agitate; <as>as,
to <ex>stir</ex> a pudding with a spoon</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My mind is troubled, like a fountain <qex>stirred</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To bring into debate; to agitate; to moot.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Stir</qex> not questions of jurisdiction.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To incite to action; to arouse; to instigate; to
prompt; to excite.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧To <xex>stir</xex> men to
devotion.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An Ate, <qex>stirring</qex> him to blood and strife.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And for her sake some mutiny will <qex>stir</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In all senses except the first, <xex>stir</xex> is often
followed by <xex>up</xex> with an intensive effect; as, to
<xex>stir</xex> up fire; to <xex>stir</xex> up sedition.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To move; incite; awaken; rouse; animate;
stimulate; excite; provoke.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stir</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stir
<hw>Stir</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To move; to change
one's position.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I had not power to <qex>stir</qex> or strive,⟦br⟧
But felt that I was still alive.</q> <rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be in motion; to be active or bustling; to exert
or busy one's self.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All are not fit with them to <qex>stir</qex> and toil.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The friends of the unfortunate exile, far from resenting his
unjust suspicions, were <qex>stirring</qex> anxiously in his behalf.</q>
<rj><qau>Merivale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To become the object of notice; to be on
foot.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They fancy they have a right to talk freely upon everything that
<qex>stirs</qex> or appears.</q> <rj><qau>I. Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To rise, or be up, in the morning.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stir</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stir
<hw>Stir</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or result of
stirring; agitation; tumult; bustle; noise or various
movements.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Why all these words, this clamor, and this <qex>stir</qex>?</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Consider, after so much <qex>stir</qex> about genus and species,
how few words we have yet settled definitions of.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Public disturbance or commotion; tumultuous
disorder; seditious uproar.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Being advertised of some <qex>stirs</qex> raised by his unnatural
sons in England.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J. Davies.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Agitation of thoughts; conflicting
passions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stirabout</ent>⟦br⟧
